I’ve been getting a lot of messages asking how I’m doing (you are all SO sweet. I’m honestly just blown away by all the kindness + encouragement 🥺) + if I’ve received my results yet from my mammogram. For those who don’t know, 2 weeks ago I found a lump in my left breast and it’s been incredibly scary since. I went to my family doctor right away and after a breast exam I was immediately referred to the hospital for a mammogram a few days later. The next day I was called back to the hospital to go over the results + do another exam. I received “good-ish” news that the tissue in my breast looks normal but I would now need to do an ultrasound to determine what the lump is. I’m thankful that the mammogram came back clear but it doesn’t rule out “the C word” as the doctor told me.
So tomorrow I go in for my ultrasound appt (Duane is coming with me thankfully 🤍) and then they said I’ll receive my results the following day. The nerves are really high as you can imagine and I’d just be SO appreciative if you would join me in prayer that this lump isn’t critical to my health + that it would resolve with simple treatment or resolve on its own. ♥️
Again, thank you all for your messages. I wish I could go through each + every one of them (there’s over 600🥺) but I just don’t have the mental capacity right now. I hope to answer them soon though.
I appreciate you all! xx

My rock. My safety blanket. ♥️
Today, after an incredibly exhausting + draining week, I got the phone call that I had been simultaneously waiting for/dreading. I spent all day pacing the house with a rock in my stomach waiting for “the call”. And at just after noon the breast health doctor called me with the results from my mammogram + ultrasound and it’s with tears streaming down my face + an INCREDIBLY thankful heart that I type this saying the lump is not cancer!! 😭

The phone call felt like a total blur. (Thankfully Duane stayed home from work to be with me when the call came in and I had it on speaker so he could absorb all the information) All the words jumbled together as it felt like no words mattered unless she said the one + only phrase I so badly wanted to hear. all I kept thinking while she was talking was “please don’t say cancer. please don’t say cancer” with my heart facing a million miles a minute and all I could blurt out in response was “so, it isn’t cancer?” I asked. To which she replied “no, it is not” and I immediately burst into tears and couldn’t muster another word. I hung up the phone and fell into Duane’s arms and just sobbed. In that moment I felt a million pounds lighter yet so feeble. 😔

Now, I’m not entirely out of the woods just yet. They still find the lump “worrisome” which isn’t comforting so I’m being referred to a surgeon for a 3rd examination and he/she will advise on what the next steps will be in regards to this lump. 
So it’s not over, but the fact that this dark cloud that has been looming over me all week is finally gone, I’m rejoicing and thanking God over and over and over again.♥️ HE. IS. GOOD. 

I’m absolutely exhausted, mentally and physically, + am clicking post on this write up and crawling into bed for the night. 🫠 but truly, more than anything, I’m just feeling GRATEFUL. For my health. I have debated posting this a thousand times over today…There’s nothing more frightening than exposing your biggest insecurities + allowing yourself to be raw and vulnerable in front of others. - Starbucks Medicine Ball Dupe - 
Sharing my favourite tea that’s JAM PACKED with nutrients + whole ingredients and the best part, it tastes soo good!!
It’s the perfect tea to combat cold + flu season and keep that immune system up! If you love the Honey Citrus Mint Tea (aka the “medicine ball” tea) from Starbucks, you’ll love this at home version! 

Recipe;
1 raw ginger root (about the size of your hand)
3 lemons
3 tbsp of raw honey 
Splash of water
Peach tea bags
Mint tea bags 

Cut the raw ginger into small chunks and toss into blender. Next, remove the skins from the lemons then cut up the rest into small chunks and toss into the blender as well. Add 3 tablespoons of raw honey and a splash of water. Blend until fully combined and smooth consistency. Next, pour into ice cube trays (regular size is best) and toss into the freezer. Once fully frozen, pop the ginger/lemon/honey cubes out of the tray and store in a ziploc bag in your freezer for easy access. When ready to make the tea, steep 1 bag of peach tea + 1 bag of mint tea in a mug of hot water for 4 minutes. Remove bags and add 1 ginger cube to the hot tea. Stir until dissolved. If you like your tea a bit sweeter, add another teaspoon of honey! 🍯 and of course you can tweak the recipe to your liking! Whether you like it more gingery/less gingery, more lemony/less lemony etc just adjust the amounts accordingly.

It has been QUITE the journey with my skin.😔 I’ve struggled with cystic acne on + off for the past 7 years but this past little bit it’s been REALLY bad. 😭 super painful + open sores are impossible to cover with makeup. It’s been a HUGE source of insecurity for me + I hated that I had to do layers of makeup just to go out. I’ve gone to countless doctors appointments + tried all the medications to control the breakouts but with no success..until recently!
I’ve been dreading sharing these clips because honestly, it’s been something I’ve been SO self conscious about for so long! But a lot you have been noticing a change in my skin + are also looking for remedies for your own skin struggles. So now that I’ve FINALLY got it under control, I couldn’t not share what’s worked for me. (*emphasis on what’s worked for ME. I am no doctor or dermatologist, I can only share my experience and what made a drastic difference with my skin*)
So I hope sharing this helps even just ONE person out there who’s been walking this same path of trying to feel confident in their own skin. 🤍 all these videos are with zero makeup, filters or edits of course!

So here is what worked for me;
1.) PROGESTERONE! Without getting into too much of my medical history, my hormone levels were all out of whack so my wonderful Naturopath caught that and prescribed me a progesterone cream medication that I apply every night on my forearms before bed. THIS I feel has made the biggest difference! 
2.) LOW STRESS WORKOUT. My cortisol levels were also off the charts so my NP advised I take a step back from high intensity workouts + instead sub out for low impact exercise such as Pilates/yoga. Now, I know LOTS of women who do high intensity workouts and their skin is glowing so everyone is different! 
3.) ZERO. DAIRY. I have been dairy free for years but I would eat minimal dairy here + there if someone made me a meal or i was at a restaurant. But now I’m really strict on NO dairy + it’s helped a lot with breakouts and inflammation in my face!

When out + about with the kids, I often get the “oh she is your mini-me!” when referencing the physical similarities between Georgia/Hallie and I. (And don’t get me wrong, I LOVE it!) but as my children are growing up + understanding the references/adult conversation, I’m realizing the weight that words can hold as they standby and digest these (innocent enough) DNA-comparing comments. Truthfully though, it just makes me feel sad for Noa that she won’t have a stranger approach us and exclaim those same comments about her and I looking alike while strolling the grocery aisle. She won’t get the “oh you have your mum’s hair!” or “you definitely have your dad’s eyes!” It’s just the reality of being an adoptive family. I don’t want her to feel alienated or any less so I try to shield her from some of these situations but it’s hard because…well, life..
But today when Noa got in the truck and noticed me wearing my sunglasses, she said “one sec” and ran back inside. Minutes later she came running back out with her sunnies in hand. She put them on, looked at me + proudly said “Mum! Now YOU AND I are twins!!” And it made me tear up. 🥹 She was SO proud to be part of the “twinning with mum” group + we had our moment. 🤍
Adoption is interesting. The comments that I get out in public never cease to amaze me. The other day I got a new one. “Good for you for adopting and mixing it up” while motioning towards Noa. I know she meant well but it just didn’t sit right with me. Those who know Duane and I and our hearts for adoption know that we’ve done this because we WANT to adopt. This isn’t some sort of charity action, “good deed” or check off the “do-good list”. This is something we so desired in the depths of our heart. Something we were called to do. It’s part of who we are so much that it comes as natural to us as a biological mother referring to her biological children. To us, there is no difference. There is no hesitation. She is my daughter, my girl, my baby. 
End. Of. Story. 
And I’ll forever, and ever, and ever be thankful to their biological mothers who chose me to be their forever mum. It often brings me to my knees (and tears) in humility to carry that honour. 🤍

to my son.. 
the boy who single-handedly healed my heart & who put colour back into my colourless world.
He was placed into my arms not as a newborn but rather a 4.5 month old little boy. A boy who I watched grow up on a screen and YEARNED for day to day updates until the moment he was finally where he belonged, with me. 🤍

He is when I feel like a part of me began.
A part that never existed before.
He bloomed one of the greatest seeds in my heart. Motherhood. 

I can never, and will never, be able to fully grasp the weight of what his incredible birthmother went through for both sawyer + I, but I do know that because of her vast and immeasurable love for her son, she entrusted me to cherish and love him for the rest of his life. And I’m writing this with tears in my eyes because most mothers don’t experience this kind of sacrificial love when one experiences the incredibly joy of becoming a mother at the expense of another’s trauma and loss. It’s understandably unfathomable for some. But today (a day late) I am grateful celebrate National Son’s Day with my sweet, caring, kind, brilliant sawyer all because of one of our mutually cherished people in this world, his birthmother. 🤍

Being sawyer’s mother is TRULY one of the greatest joys of my life and I feel like everyday someone should pinch me that I was chosen to be his mum. 🥹

So with tears streaming down our face and shattered hearts, we abided. Hand in hand we walked that dark valley October 16. 

I rarely share about this day because for the past 11 years it’s been an extremely triggering day for me and it was just easier for me get through the day acknowledging it as little as possible because i feel like it hurt less that way. To push the grief down. To keep it locked away in my heart. But yet every year this man remembers. And he acknowledges how this day will forever be embedded into our souls.

We adopted our first daughter October 9th 2012 + you could not find two more happy and proud parents than Duane and I. We were literally floating on cloud 9 and we were so MADLY in love with this little girl, our daughter. 9 gloriously beautiful days later it all came crumbling down with one short and simple phone call. “I’m so sorry Skye…. But the birth mother changed her mind and she would like you to bring back baby girl….. today.” 

I didn’t move an inch of my body for what felt like eternity, just frozen and holding my little girl, staring down at her as tears streamed down my face knowing that my moments with her were slowly dwindling. It took everything in me to call Duane and even more to even speak a word. He rushed home and the tidal wave of grief started. The rest of the day was a blur. There just aren’t words to remotely begin to explain that day for both Duane and I.
With tears steaming down our faces we slowly and numbly handed her into another’s arms. Never to be held by us again. 
 
 And so we live with this day and the weight it will forever hold in our hearts. But we also honour this story for all who played a part and in our hearts we know that it led us to our 4 beautiful children today. I’ll never know why this had to happen but I rest in knowing God is good. All the time.
So I’ll continue to praise him. not only on the mountains but also in the valleys. 🤍

Some days i can’t believe FOUR months have already passed since we started this huge reno + other days it feels like it’s been forever and I can’t remember not living in chaos…
If I’m being completely honest, these past few months have been hard on our marriage. We’re out of our normal comfort zone, everything feels disheveled, our kids feel out of sorts with no where to relax and our minds are JAM PACKED with all the decisions that come with renovations. (Decision fatigue is a real thing let me tell ya!) BUT we knew it wouldn’t be easy. It would be tolling and we’d have to fight against the pressure and stress and be intentional on finding our way back to each other over and over again.

The day we got ownership of this property both our parents came over and all 6 of us and the kids walked the 4 corners of the acreage in unity and prayed over the land and asked God to bless it. And when doing this renovation I knew I wanted bible scriptures to be embedded into the bones of our home + for it to be dedicated to God because we know without Him and His new mercies and grace everyday, we wouldn’t be where we are. So before the drywall’s installed, we sat together as a family all piled onto a stack of drywall and took turns praying out loud together, named our blessings and thanked Jesus for each one of them. We then got a sharpie each, played our family’s favourite worship song (“The Blessing”) on the speaker and each of us picked a few verses and wrote them on the studs of our home. It was one of the most beautiful nights I’ve witnessed with my family + maybe, just maybe, one day there will be another renovation (waaaaay down the road when I’m an old lady) and we’ll see those scriptures still there, written by a 10,7,5 + 4 year old, solid as ever and holding the same truths they’ve always had. 🤍

As a family we’re reflecting this christmas season because we know it can be joyful in so many ways but for some it’s an extremely difficult time of year. In our communities there are those who struggle with loneliness, food insecurities and facing this cold weather with no shelter or warm clothing. So partnering alongside @ranmission.ca was a heart project and the kids and I were more than happy to step up for those who need it. 🤍

For those who aren’t familiar with Ruth & Naomi’s Mission;
+ They support 28 men and women in bed-based addiction recovery
+ They serve 380 meals PER DAY(!) and provide 24/7 care
+ They operate rooms for 59 individuals who are stepping out of homelessness and into supportive housing
+ They manage 36 apartment units for low-income families with security and supports
+ They offer 100+ shelter beds each night, plus provisions for basic hygience and clothing needs.

We asked Ruth & Naomi’s how we could support them this season, and they said a huge blessing would be to help them spread awareness about their organization so by simply following them here on Instagram + showing their page some love! 

They also needed toques and gloves so we picked some up as well as their most needed grocery items (peanut butter, canned meats, oatmeal + canned soup) and dropped it off at their drop off location to some very grateful hands. It was a day that spurred some very important conversations with the kids and it gave them a new perspective that was so eye opening for them. It’s also a way we can reflect on all the privileges we get everyday and to remember the true meaning of Christmas. And that’s to take care of our neighbours. Join us this holiday season in the spirit of giving.
